  "description": "Evidence is the substrate for identification and verification. Provide media and metadata that allow another person to independently assess the observation.\n¶Practice guidance Capture diagnostic features across multiple angles (e.g., leaf arrangement, dorsal vs. ventral views). Include scale cues or habitat context when relevant. Verify date, time, and location accuracy before upload, especially for imported photos with incorrect EXIF data. If the organism is not visible, record indirect evidence (tracks, scat, galls) only when diagnostic features are clear. ¶Taxon-specific evidence notes Plants: include leaves, stems, flowers, and fruit if available; single floral shots are often insufficient. Fungi: capture substrate and underside features; spore-bearing structures are critical for ID. Insects: include dorsal and lateral views; wing venation or antennae can be diagnostic. Birds: note behavior and vocalizations; attach audio when possible. ¶Metadata matters Poor metadata yields unusable records even if the ID is correct. Precision and accuracy are different: precise coordinates that are wrong are worse than imprecise but honest ones. If you are unsure of a location, widen the accuracy radius rather than guessing.\n",
  "name": "Evidence: photos, sounds, and metadata",
